Issues.Body:
[CSS Layers](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/@layer) is a new CSS feature that lets developers organize their CSS into layers, giving better control over specificity. Chrome and Firefox support this feature, and it has now landed in the Safari Technology Preview. 

It appears that Angular's style encapsulation bails out when encountering this new syntax. Style rules declared in a `@layer` declaration are not encapsulated:

```css
/* This will not be encapsulated */
@layer utilities {
  p {
    color: darkgreen;
  }
}

/* This will be encapsulated */
p {
  font-size: 40px;
}
```

Emits:
```html
<style>
  @layer utilities {
    p {
      color: darkgreen;
    }
  }

  p[_ngcontent-mvb-c45] {
    font-size: 40px;
  }
</style>
```

**Reproduction:** https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-ivy-qce65m?file=src%2Fapp%2Fapp.component.css

### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

In my application I am using a decorator `@DynamicComponent` to marks components that can later be rendered using `viewContainerRef.createComponent(...)` (see the guide for [dynamic component loading](https://angular.io/guide/dynamic-component-loader)).

```javascript
@DynamicComponent('hello')
@Component({ template: `<h1>Hello Angular</h1>` })
export class HelloComponent {}
```
The decorator registers the component with a string on a static map.
```javascript
export function DynamicComponent(name: string) {
  return (ctor) => {
    componentRegistry.set(name, ctor);
  };
}
export const componentRegistry = new Map<string, any>();
```
Later the same string can be used to find the component and to load/create it dynamically.
```javascript
@Component({ template: `<ng-template anchor></ng-template>` })
export class AppComponent implements OnInit {
  @ViewChild(AnchorDirective, { static: true }) anchorHost!: AnchorDirective;
  ngOnInit() {
    const viewContainerRef = this.anchorHost.viewContainerRef;
    viewContainerRef.clear();
    const component = componentRegistry.get('hello');
    viewContainerRef.createComponent(component);
  }
}
```
This works fine in development mode.

However, in production (`ng serve --configuration production`) the decorators are never executed because Ivy believes the components are not used/needed.
This is because the dynamic components are only used in the modules where they are declared.
The moment I write some dummy code using the dynamic component (e.g. `new HelloComponent()`) everything works fine again.

I provided a stackblitz below where this is implemented.
In stackblitz everything is working fine because it is started in development mode.
To run it in production mode download the stackblitz example and run `npm install --force && npm start`.

